While hot springs may emerge from the ground as {{ill|colorless|en|Colorless}} and {{ill|transparent|en|Transparency and translucency}}, changes in {{ill|oxidation|en|Redox}} or {{ill|pressure|en|Pressure}} after reaching the surface can alter their composition and cause coloration. Some hot springs also have naturally colored {{ill|source water|ja|源泉|1=Spring Mouth}}. The opacity and coloration are caused by transformations in components such as {{ill|sulfur|en|Sulfur}} or {{ill|calcium|en|Calcium}}.<ref>[http://www.onsen-shinsengumi.com/nigori.html 温泉新選組]</ref> For example, milky white waters are colored by {{ill|yunohana|ja|湯の花|1=Yunohana|1=Yunohana}} formed from oxidized sulfur compounds.

