While hot springs may emerge from the ground as {{ill|colorless|en|Colorless|12=draft}} and {{ill|transparent|en|Transparency and translucency|12=draft}}, changes in {{ill|oxidation|en|Redox|12=draft}} or {{ill|pressure|en|Pressure|12=draft}} after reaching the surface can alter their composition and cause coloration. Some hot springs also have naturally colored {{ill|source water|ja|源泉|1=Spring Mouth|1=Spring Mouth|12=draft}}. The opacity and coloration are caused by transformations in components such as {{ill|sulfur|en|Sulfur|12=draft}} or {{ill|calcium|en|Calcium|12=draft}}.<ref>[http://www.onsen-shinsengumi.com/nigori.html 温泉新選組]</ref> For example, milky white waters are colored by {{ill|yunohana|ja|湯の花|1=Yunohana|1=Yunohana|12=draft}} formed from oxidized sulfur compounds.

